## The recurring promise

A one-on-one is a predictable private space for the direct report’s work experience, risks, relationships, growth, and support. It is not a weekly friendship ritual or a duplicate status meeting. Its value compounds when the manager protects the time, listens, and follows through.

## Prepare without scripting the person

Review the last commitments and choose one question shaped to the person’s current context. Let the direct report add topics in whatever lightweight way works. Do not require a polished agenda as the admission price for your attention.

## Use the time for what other meetings cannot carry

Start with their topics. Scan changed risk, then explore decisions, uncertainty, energy, relationships, and growth. Listen for meaning before fixing. A short silence is not a system failure. Keep manager updates bounded and move routine project reporting elsewhere.

## Close the loop

End with the few commitments that actually emerged: who will do what, and by when. The manager’s reliability after the meeting is part of the meeting. Brief notes should support follow-through, not become a secret narrative about the person.

## Common failure modes

If the person always says “nothing,” change the conditions and questions. If every meeting becomes status, repair the information system. If you keep canceling, acknowledge the pattern and redesign the calendar before asking for trust.

> **Boundary:** explain the limits of confidentiality. Route safety, harassment, discrimination, retaliation, health, and other formal concerns through the appropriate process.
